features: AN600 is the new generation of DeepCool low profile cpu cooling solution for mid-level small form-factor systems that require a short high-performance CPU cooler thanks to the compact design of minimalism

DeepCool AN600 low profile CPU air cooler features six pieces 6mm nickel plated heatpipes with raised copper coldplate to maximize heat dissipation to overall 180w TDP cooling capacity with the thermal paste contained in package

Slim 120mm PWM enabled-FDB fan on AN600 low profile CPU air cooler features the latest DeepCool “three-phase six-pole” motor to build a low-noise cooling system with extra stable airflow. Meanwhile, a low-noise adapter cable is included in the box for quieter using experience

The slim 120mm fan features maximum 1850RPM fan speed which pushes 61.56CFM airflow through the fin array and down onto the RAM and VRMs below for better cooling performance, noise damping pads in fan corners avoid vibration and keep noise level under 24.4dB(A) even in full load

67mm tall AN600 low profile CPU cooler was designed to be compatible with different motherboards in two installations for better compatibility, Installation A features 100% RAM clearance with 42mm hight for I/O; Installation B is compatible with maximum 40mm of RAM clearance. Please check the fourth infographic to learn more details about installation

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Using it in a challenging situation: Fractal Ridge + 5900x
reviews.reviewText: Install: I didn’t have to do any mods or tweaks but the power cable is tight in Fractal. If you losen it and then put the cooler in then tighten it fits ok. Others i saw were using standoffs to hang the plug out. You can do that too, but i didn't need to.Cooling wise in a 64 degree house, the cpu, 5900x, will climb up to 70’s (max) under usage with a pretty strong fan ramp in a small form factor case (the ridge). Its acceptable, but don’t expect any kind of magic or dead silent fan but you can tame even higher powered cpus with the right tweaks well. I can get it closer to what you would expect in a large case with a larger cooler if i turn off pbo, and am careful with cable placement. I'll run it in the 30's-40s with general computing. I also use fan curve software. THe 5900x runs a similar heat level to most higher end desktop cpus and that's a very small case, with a beefy gpu by the way so this fan does work. By the way my fist attempt was lack luster i had to remount with a bit more paste. Your tolerances are very tight with coolers, more so in these challenging situations.Here is a comparison, I’ve also got a 13900k which is much hotter than this but its on a d15 and far away from my head and i don’t normally hear it unless im running a compile and that’s also in a gigantic tower with a lot of supporting cooling. i’ not saying the cooler is bad it’s really good, or the case is bad or the cpu is bad. The combination is just pushing it, it can be done, it’s not bad if you fiddle a bunch with fan curvs and get everything else right in your build (really clean).THe funny thing is this is a cooler that 's really goign to be put into much harder situations than many larger coolers, in general, so just keep that in mind for best results. SFX is a lot of fun, but it can take some fiddeling up wards of 20c quite easily with some adjustments. II will say that it’ s a good cooler. Have realistic expectations though with a cpu like a 5900x in a sfx case like the ridge. One issue with the ridge is the air flow can create some resonance and the fans are fairy close to the grill. I had to fiddle with fan curve quite a bit, actually that case is great, and the cooler as wel but it's also pushing the size of what that case can handle the closer you get to the grill the louder the fans get, and that means you have to slow them down. the physical install was really easy, but the main issue is just tweaking and tweaking until you can quiet case and the power plug in that case is gigantic and takes some finess. My case is pretty close to my head and the fan is pointed right at me so it’s not the most forgiving.The other thing that’s great about this cooler is the ram compat is fantastic.My opinion overall is this cooler is kind of the definition of threading the needle. That’s a compliment.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 20, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Great Cooler - Not Compatible w/ AMD systems in Fractal Ridge
reviews.reviewText: This is a great SFF cooler that has a great mounting system and has lots of headroom for newer CPUs. But unfortunately case compatibility is still an issue with this cooler, at least for AMD systems. I tried using this cooler in the Fractal Ridge with an AMD build and in both directions the Ridge's power extension cord was in the way. If there was a second set of brackets included for AMD systems I might have been able to rotated it sideways and have it fit. Intel builds won't have this issue since you can install it four ways instead of two. Replacement power extension cords do exist but they're hard to find and of questionable quality. Go with another cooler if you are building an AMD system in the Fractal Ridge case.

reviews.reviewTitle: Low profile, great heat dissipation and quiet at full speed
reviews.reviewText: The DeepCool AN600 low profile CPU cooler is a high quality product that is capable of cooling most of today's processors. The cooler is able to dissipate heat in my i7 8700K known for being a hot chip when under full load.The device is well made and easy to install with many accessories included that allow the cooler to cover a wide variety of chipsets from both AMD and intel. The fan is a bit loud at full load when it's at around 1850rpm.Compared to a 360mm AIO water cooler the AN600 impressed me with its abilities. The fan is able to keep the CPU almost as cool as the AIO water cooler within 8C. The fan comes closer to the AIO water cooler ability as eventually the radiator of the AIO gets saturated with heat and looses its ability to keep the CPU at a low temperature during spikes, the AN600 does not have this issue and quickly cools the chip after putting it under load for extended periods.The cooler comes with thermal paste however I used a high quality one from another manufacturer to ensure plbest performance from the device and make comparison to the water cooler that I normally use.Overall this is a great quality product that is easy to install and looks great with its low profile (some coolers can be massive). Great value from a reputable manufacturer considering the price point. This cooler may not have RGB lighting or look as nice as other coolers however it works great and has a good price especially on sale.

reviews.reviewTitle: Ich bin beeindruckt, viel besser als der Noctua NH-L9x65.
reviews.reviewText: Dieser CPU-Kühler ist um Welten besser als der Noctua NH-L9x65 (den ich vorher drinne hatte). Er kühlt meinen i5-13600k bei Vollast (Cinebench23, 120W PL1+PL2) immer auf unter 65°C, beim Noctua ging die Temperatur auf lärmende 90°C hoch. Denke das liegt am wesentlich breiteren Kühlkörper, den 6 Headpipes und vor allem am mächtigen 120mm Lüfter, der nicht so schnell wie der kleine 92mm Noctua aufdrehen muss.

空冷で冷却効果の高い物は、ファンが縦置きで高さ制限に引っかかるのですが、これだと大丈夫。マザーボードとの取り付けも、ベース金具を上下でガッチリ固定した上で取り付けるので安定して付けられる。この金具類だけでも、価格に見合う価値が有ります。ただ、最後のファンの取り付けは、ファンの隙間からドラバー突っ込んで止めるんで、結構大変やったけど、Asusのマザーボードにちゃんと付きました。性能は、CPU付属のリテールファンより断然冷えると思います。

I've been using this with an AM5 motherboard - I recently got a AMD Ryzen 5 7600 processor. Fits well and includes all the necessary accessories. After using it for the past month, it has been noticeably quieter compared to the stock Wraith cooler provided by AMD.Overall, no concerns with this product.

Very neatly processed.Very silent.Cooling 12600k optimally. Highest recorded temp around 78 Degrees with set to intakeWorks very well in slim tower cases like Fractal Ridge (only one problem is the fractal ridges PSU Cable - it is in the way, not the fault of the cooler)
